== Usage ==
CargoDest is easy enough to use: Once it is enable in the GUI or the configuration file (openttd.cfg in most cases), the cargo will find its routes themselves. The Routing Network is built up using the orders of the vehicles. If you have two vehicles, one which goes from A to B and another from B to C, there will be cargo that wishes to from A to C. In this case, the cargo at A will board '''''any''''' vehicle that goes to B (The ''transfer station''), leave there and then use '''''any''''' vehicle that goes to C. Any vehicle implies any vehicle going directly from A to B, vehicles with have a stopover in D (thus go A-D-B) will not be used.

{{en/Note|When your vehicles have Transfer orders, they will be ignored, the cargodest system handles it automatically. Transfer orders don't break anything, they're also not removed, they just act like any normal order does}}

[[File:en/Community/Patches/Addroute.png|frame|center]]
It should be noted that for the purpose of Routing Network, any stopover a vehicle has (a ''transit station'') is treated exactly like a ''transfer station''.

Nothing needs to be done to build up the routing system, see the example on the right.

The first four orders don't add any route from one station to another, but they're there for some kind of realistic depot usage of the train.

However, as order #5 is inserted, the routing system parses the new data and adds a new ''edge'' from Badinghead (Station <0>) to Senpool(<1>). It also adds an edge for the return trip. Both edges get a cost of 105, and are shown in the minimap.

The route is added both for passengers and mail as it seems that the train can carry both types of cargo.

